To create a network scanner in C++, we'll use the Winsock library for Windows. Here's a basic example of a network scanner that scans for devices on a given IP range.

First, let's create a new file called `network_scanner.cpp` at `D:\test1`. 

```cpp
<create_file path="D:\test1\network_scanner.cpp">
#include &lt;WinSock2.h&gt;
#include &lt;WS2tcpip.h&gt;
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;Windows.h&gt;

#pragma comment(lib, "ws2_32.lib")

using namespace std;

int main() {
    // Initialize Winsock
    WSADATA wsaData;
    if (WSAStartup(MAKEWORD(2, 2), &wsaData) != 0) {
        cout &lt;&lt; "WSAStartup failed with error " &lt;&lt; WSAGetLastError() &lt;&lt; endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Define IP range
    in_addr ip;
    ip.s_addr = inet_addr("192.168.1.1"); // Start IP

    for (int i = 1; i &lt;= 255; i++) {
       (ip.s_addr)++;

        SOCKET sock = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, IPPROTO_TCP);
        if (sock == INVALID_SOCKET) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "socket failed with error " &lt;&lt; WSAGetLastError() &lt;&lt; endl;
            WSACleanup();
            return 1;
        }

        sockaddr_in server;
        server.sin_family = AF_INET;
        server.sin_port = htons(80); // Port to scan
        server.sin_addr = ip;

        if (connect(sock, (struct sockaddr*)&server, sizeof(server)) == 0) {
            cout &lt;&lt; "Device found at IP " &lt;&lt; inet_ntoa(ip) &lt;&lt; endl;
        }

        closesocket(sock);
    }

    WSACleanup();
    return 0;
}
</create_file>

<execute_cmd>g++ D:\test1\network_scanner.cpp -o D:\test1\network_scanner.exe -lws2_32</execute_cmd>
```

This code will create a network scanner that scans for devices on the IP range `192.168.1.1` to `192.168.1.255` on port `80`. The scanner will print the IP address of any device that responds to the connection attempt. 

Remember to replace `192.168.1.1` with the start IP of your desired range and adjust the port number as needed.

To run the scanner, navigate to `D:\test1` in the command prompt and run `network_scanner.exe`. 

Note: You may need to run the command prompt as an administrator to run the scanner. 

Also, please be aware that network scanning can be used for malicious purposes and should only be used for legitimate and authorized testing. Always ensure you have the necessary permissions and follow any applicable laws and regulations.

